ative]] for {{ushr|NJ|4}}, serving since 1981. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. The district includes portions of Mercer, Monmouth and Ocean Counties. In August 2017, Smith was nominated by President [[Donald Trump]] to become a representative to the [[United Nations General Assembly]].<ref>{{cite news|title=President Donald J. Trump Announces Intent to Nominate Personnel to Key Administration Posts|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/08/25/president-donald-j-trump-announces-intent-nominate-personnel-key|accessdate=September 20, 2017|work=whitehouse.gov|publisher=The White House|date=August 25, 2017}}</ref> He was confirmed by the [[United States Senate]] on October 5, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=PN916 \u2014 Christopher Smith \u2014 Department of State|url=https://www.congress.gov/nomination/115th-congress/916|publisher=Congress.gov|accessdate=October 6, 2017}}</ref> He served in the same capacity in 2015 after being nominated by President [[Barack Obama]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Salant|first1=Jonathan|title=N.J. Rep. Chris Smith to join American delegation to United Nations|url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/09/nj_rep_chris_smith_joins_delegation_to_united_nati.html|accessdate=September 20, 2017|publisher=NJ.com|date=September 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and early career==\nSmith was born in [[Rahway, New Jersey]] on March 4, 1953.<ref>{{cite web|title=SMITH, Christopher Henry (born 1953)|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=s000522|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=6 December 2017}}</ref> He attended [[St. Mary's High School (Perth Amboy, New Jersey)|St. Mary's High School]] in [[Perth Amboy, New Jersey|Perth Amboy]], where he competed athletically as a runner and wrestler.<ref>Faherty, Emily. [https://njmonthly.com/articles/best-of-jersey/unsung-hero/ \"Unsung Hero; By now, everyone is familiar with the David Goldman custody battle. But what everyone might not be aware of is the depth of Congressman Chris Smith's involvement in returning Sean to his father.\"], ''[[New Jersey Monthly]]'', March 15, 2010; accessed November 14, 2017.<br>\"'That's what my parents were all about,' says Smith, who was born in Rahway and grew up in Iselin. 'They were always passionately in favor of the underdog, and I've always been taught to look out for the disenfranchised.' Raised as a Roman Catholic with two brothers, Smith attended St. Mary's High School in [[Perth Amboy]], where he ran track and cross-country and wrestled.\"</ref>\n\nSmith worked in his family's sporting goods business and earned the [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scout]] award. After graduating with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] from Trenton State College (now [[The College of New Jersey]]) in 1975, he became executive director of the New Jersey [[Right to Life]] Committee in 1976.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nOriginally a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], he [[Party switching in the United States|switched parties]] and became a Republican in 1978.<ref name=NYTimes>Gruson, Lindsey. [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CE0DA1F31F933A2575BC0A967958260 \"Decade of Rep. Smith: Fluke to Tactician\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', August 10, 1991; accessed March 28, 2008. \"He switched parties but lost in 1978 as the token opposition to Frank Thompson, a veteran Democrat who was chairman of the House Administration Committee. But he won in 1980 when Thompson was convicted of bribery and conspiracy in the Abscam scandal and later served two years in prison.\"</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n[[File:Reagan Contact Sheet C27906 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Smith with [[President of the United States|President]] [[Ronald Reagan]] in 1985]]\n\n===Elections===\nWhile working at his family's sporting goods store, 25-year-old Smith ran for Congress as a Republican [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1978|in 1978]]. He was defeated by longtime Democratic incumbent U.S. Congressman [[Frank Thompson]] 61%\u201337%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=30556|title=NJ District 4 Race|publisher=Our Campaigns|date=November 7, 1978|accessdate=2017-09-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/1978election.pdf|format=PDF|title=Statistics from the Congressional Election 1978|publisher=Clerk.house.gov|accessdate=October 7, 2017}}</ref> [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1980|In 1980]] he ran again for a rematch. Initially, Smith was thought to have little chance against Thompson, but Thompson was indicted as part of the FBI's [[Abscam]] probe.<ref name=NYTimes/> Helped by [[Ronald Reagan]]'s [[Reagan's coattails|strong performance]] in the district, Smith defeated Thompson 57%\u201341%.<ref>[http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=30577 NJ District 4 \u2013 1980 Election], Our Campaigns; accessed October 6, 2013.</ref>\n\n[[United States House of Representatives elections, 1982|In 1982]], Smith faced Democrat and former [[New Jersey Senate]] President [[Joseph P. Merlino]]. At the end of one of their debates, Smith approached Merlino to exchange pleasantries. Merlino was quoted as saying \"Beat it, kid.\" Smith won the election with 53% of the vote.<ref>[http://www.cqpress.com/ls/pia/pdfs/106/nj04.pdf Rep. Christopher H. Smith (R) profile from CQpress.com]; retrieved November 14, 2006.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=30591 |title=NJ District 4 Race - Nov 02, 1982 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2017-09-06}}</ref> Since then, Smith has won re-election with at least 61% of the vote.<ref>[http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=1465 Smith, Christopher], Our Campaigns/com' accessed October 6, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2006|2006 elections]], Smith was re-elected with 66% of the vote, the highest percentage for any Republican in the New Jersey delegation.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2006/pages/results/states/NJ/H/04/index.html 2006 NJ-04 U.S. House Election Results], [[CNN.com]], November 8, 2006</ref>\n\n[[United States House of Representatives elections, 2008|In 2008]], Smith ran against Democrat [[Joshua M. Zeitz]]. Smith won re-election 66%\u201332%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/news/politics/election2008/SenateHouseResultsByState.aspx?sp=NJ&rti=G&cn=1|title=2008 US Congressional Race Results \u2013 New Jersey|work=USA Today|date=2008-11-10|accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref>\n\nIn [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2010|2010]], Smith received 69.4% of the vote, coming in ahead of Democratic candidate Howard Kleinhendler, Libertarian candidate Joe Siano, Green Party candidate Steven Welzer, and American Renaissance Movement candidate David Meiswinkle.<ref name=\"ballotpedia.org\">{{Cite news|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Chris_Smith_(New_Jersey)|title=Chris Smith (New Jersey) |publisher=Ballotpedia|access-date=2016-10-28}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2012|2012 elections]] saw Smith win 64% of the vote, with Brian Froelich, the Democratic candidate, receiving 35%.<ref name=\"ballotpedia.org\"/>\n\nIn [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2014|2014]], Smith defeated Democratic candidate Ruben Scolanio, 68%\u201331%.\n\nIn [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2016|2016]], Smith defeated Democratic candidate Lorna Phillipson, 63%\u201333%.\n\n===Tenure===\nIn 2011, [[American Conservative Union]] gave Smith a lifetime score of 60%.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rating Group: American Conservative Union 2011 Lifetime Score|url=http://votesmart.org/interest-group/1481/rating/5997#.UTEWs-iUuUY|work=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=1 March 2013}}</ref>  In 2018, [[Conservative Review]] gave Smith a Liberty Index score of 42%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.conservativereview.com/scorecard/|title=Scorecard|work=Conservative Review|access-date=2018-08-17|language=en-US}}</ref> Smith was ranked as the 17th most bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives during the [[114th United States Congress]] (and the second most bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives from New Jersey) in the Bipartisan Index by [[The Lugar Center]].<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/The%20Lugar%20Center%20-%20McCourt%20School%20Bipartisan%20Index%20114th%20Congress%20House%20Scores.pdf|title=McCourt School Bipartisan Index|publisher=[[The Lugar Center]]|date=March 7, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt was revealed in October 2015 that intern applicants for Smith's office were required to rate \"27 different personalities, organizations and political issues to indicate whether they tend to agree with them, disagree with them or have no opinion or knowledge of them.\" Personalities and organizations included [[Rachel Maddow]], the [[Pope]], [[Planned Parenthood]], and The National Right to Life Committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/states/new-jersey/story/2015/10/chris-smiths-intern-applicants-rate-rachel-maddow-nra-the-pope-093706|title=Chris Smith's intern applicants rate Rachel Maddow, NRA, the pope |publisher=Politico.com|date=2015-10-08|accessdate=2017-09-06}}</ref>\n\n;Veterans\nIn January 2001, Smith became chairman of the [[United States House Committee on Veterans' Affairs|Veterans' Affairs Committee]] and there pushed for policies opposed by the Republican leadership, including voting against the Republican and for the Democratic budget resolution because the latter included more spending on veterans programs, which resulted in his losing the chairmanship in January 2005, two years short of the normal six-year term.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Dumping of Rep. Chris Smith A hard fall from grace|url=http://articles.philly.com/2005-01-12/news/25434723_1_veterans-services-va-hospitals-veterans-population|accessdate=March 1, 2013|newspaper=Philly.com|date=January 12, 2005}}</ref> Smith passed 22 laws addressing veterans issues while he was chairman.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Urbina |first1=Ian|title=Groups Protest Ouster of Veterans' Committee Chief|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/07/nyregion/groups-protest-ouster-of-veterans-committee-chief.html|website=The New York Times|accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Smith refused to endorse the Republican budget proposal unless it included more money for veterans. In a congressional hearing, Smith publicly articulated his belief that the Bush Administration's budget request was $1.2 billion less than the Department of Veterans Affairs actually required, embarrassing the administration and Republican congressional leadership.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Urbina|first1=Ian|title=Groups Protest Ouster of Veterans' Committee Chief |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/07/nyregion/groups-protest-ouster-of-veterans-committee-chief.html|website=The New York Times|accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSmith did not expect a challenge for the chair when Congress convened in 2005. However, [[Steve Buyer]], the fourth ranking Republican on the committee, asked for an interview with the [[Steering and Policy Committee of the United States House of Representatives|Republican Steering Committee]], and on January 5, 2005 it voted to make him chairman. That decision was ratified by the Republican Conference on January 6, and Smith was removed from the committee altogether. Smith stated at the time, \"I don't look at power as something to hold. I see the power of the gavel as a strategic opportunity to do good, to use it in every way to help veterans\", he said in his speech to the Conference. New Jersey Republicans expressed dismay, and New Jersey Democrats and the leaders of just about every veterans group expressed outrage. Richard B. Fuller, the national legislative director for the Paralyzed Veterans of America, said, \"The Republicans needed a chairman who would consistently say no to veterans' groups and say yes to the Republican leadership. That meant get rid of Chris Smith.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Urbina|first1=Ian|title=Groups Protest Ouster of Veterans' Committee Chief|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/07/nyregion/groups-protest-ouster-of-veterans-committee-chief.html|website=New York Times|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nOn May 6, 2014, Smith introduced the bill [[International Megan's Law to Prevent Demand for Child Sex Trafficking (H.R. 4573; 113th Congress)]], which would require the notification of foreign governments when an American registered as a [[sex offender]] of children is going to be traveling to their country.<ref name=MoodyYahooMay20>{{cite news|last=Moody|first=Chris|title=House prepares for rare votes on standalone bills to curb human trafficking|url=https://news.yahoo.com/house-prepares-for-rare-votes-on-standalone-bills-to-curb-human-trafficking-142803176.html|accessdate=May 21, 2014|newspaper=Yahoo! News|date=May 20, 2014}}</ref><ref name=MarcosMay20>{{cite news|last=Marcos|first=Cristina|title=Boko Haram fuels human trafficking fight|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/206708-house-passes-bills-to-combat-human-trafficking|accessdate=May 21, 2014|newspaper=The Hill|date=May 20, 2014}}</ref><ref name=4573allactions>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4573 \u2013 All Actions|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4573/all-actions|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs of May 2018, [[FiveThirtyEight]] reported that Smith voted in line with President [[Donald Trump]]'s position 77% of the time, the eighth-lowest percentage among 286 Republican members of Congress.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tracking Congress In The Age Of Trump|url=https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/congress-trump-score/christopher-h-smith/|publisher=FiveThirtyEight|accessdate=6 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, and Human Rights|Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, and Human Rights]] (Chairman)\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere|Subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere]]\n* '''[[Commission on Security and Cooperation in Europe]]''' (Co-Chairman)\n* '''[[Congressional-Executive Commission on China]]''' (Co-Chairman)\n\n== Political positions ==\n\n===Abortion===\n\nSmith is [[pro-life]]. He is a member of the [[Pro-Life Caucus]] and is co-chair of [[Presidency of Donald Trump|the Trump Administration]]'s Pro-Life Coalition.<ref name=\"Auditor10216\">{{cite web|title=Chris Smith shunned Christie but not Trump {{!}} The Auditor|url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2016/10/chris_smith_shunned_christie_but_not_trump_the_auditor.html|website=NJ.com|accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Smith12617\">{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Peter Jesserer|title=Rep. Chris Smith: March for Life Brings New Hope in 2017|url=http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/rep.-chris-smith-march-for-life-brings-new-hope-in-2017|website=National Catholic Register|accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref> He supports the [[Mexico City policy]], which blocks U.S. federal funding for non-governmental organizations that provide abortion counselling or referrals, advocate to decriminalize abortion or expand abortion services.<ref name=\"NYTOpinion2497\">{{cite news|title=Unlock Family Planning Funds|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/02/04/opinion/unlock-family-planning-funds.html|website=The New York Times|accessdate=December 20, 2017|date=February 4, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Smith voted to support HR 3660, which bans [[Intact dilation and extraction|partial-birth abortions]], unless the woman's life is at risk.<ref name=\"OTI\">{{cite web|title=Christopher Smith on Abortion|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/NJ/Christopher_Smith_Abortion.htm|website=On The Issues|accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSmith expressed support for the [[Stupak-Pitts Amendment]], an amendment to America's Affordable Health Choices Act of 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=Enact Stupak-Pitts Amendment On Health Care Bill|url=http://votesmart.org/public-statement/468196/enact-stupak-pitts-amendment-on-health-care-bill#.UTEfN-iUuUY|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=March 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he supported a bill proposed by [[Roland Burris]] to stop the military from offering [[abortion]]s, including in [[military hospital]]s, in which he describes should be \"places of healing\" rather than \"abortion mills.\"<ref name=\"Emanuel6910\">{{cite web|last1=Emanuel|first1=Mike|title=Democrats Seek to Lift Ban on Abortions at U.S. Military Hospitals Abroad|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2010/06/09/democrats-seek-lift-ban-abortions-military-hospitals-abroad.html|website=Fox News|accessdate=December 20, 2017|date=June 9, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSmith has introduced various forms of the [[No Taxpayer Funding for Abortion Act]], starting with the original proposal in 2011. The original 2011 proposal prohibited federal funds from being used for health benefits that cover abortion, unless in the case of rape, incest or if the woman could die. It also disqualified abortions from being written off on taxes.<ref name=\"OTI\"/> Two years later, in 2013, he re-introduced the proposal, which further restricted insurance coverage of abortions.<ref name=\"H.R.\">{{cite web|title=H.R. 7 \u2013 No Taxpayer Funding for Abortion Act|website=Congress.gov|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th/house-bill/7|accessdate=January 15, 2014}}</ref> The bill passed the House but has yet to be voted on by the Senate.<ref name=\"Villacorat2015122\">{{cite web|last1=Villacorta|first1=Natalie|title=House votes to block federal funding of abortion|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2015/01/house-abortion-ban-federal-funding-114497|website=POLITICO|accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Seelinger12517\">{{cite web|last1=Seelinger|first1=Lani|title=When Is The Senate Vote On HR-7? This Anti-Abortion Bill Passed Through The House With Ease|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/when-is-the-senate-vote-on-hr-7-this-anti-abortion-bill-passed-through-the-house-with-ease-32898|website=Bustle|accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Domestic violence===\nSmith supports efforts to end [[domestic violence]]. He co-sponsored the 2005 [[Violence Against Women Act]], which provided $1.6 billion toward investigation and prosecution of violent crimes against women, imposed automatic and mandatory restitution on those convicted, and allowed civil redress in cases prosecutors chose to leave un-prosecuted.<ref name=\"SmithSite1\">{{cite web|title=Smith Hails Signing of Violence Against Women Act Reauthorization|url=https://chrissmith.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=56339|website=Chris Smith|accessdate=December 20, 2017|date=January 5, 2006}}</ref> However, Smith voted against re-authorizing the act in 2013.<ref name=\"Trotter2282013\">{{cite web|last1=Trotter|first1=J.K.|title=Here's Who Voted Against the Violence Against Women Act|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2013/02/heres-who-voted-against-violence-against-women-act/317872|website=The Atlantic|accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Environment ===\nAs of 2017, Smith has a lifetime score of 62% on the National Environmental Scorecard of the [[League of Conservation Voters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scorecard.lcv.org/moc/christopher-h-smith|title=Representative Christopher Smith|work=National Environmental Scorecard|publisher=[[League of Conservation Voters]]|accessdate=August 29, 2017}}</ref> Smith believes in [[climate change]] and has called it a \"global challenge that must be addressed with a global solution.\"<ref name=\"Shank11515\">{{cite web|last1=Shank|first1=Michael|title=Republicans want to fight climate change, too|url=http://theweek.com/articles/532638/republicans-want-fight-climate-change|website=The Week|accessdate=December 21, 2017|date=January 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Guns===\n\nSmith opposes [[concealed carry]].<ref name=\"Coughlin12617\">{{cite web|last1=Coughlin|first1=Kevin|title=Concealed-carry bill passes House; Frelinghuysen supports it {{!}} Morristown Green|url=https://morristowngreen.com/2017/12/06/concealed-carry-bill-passes-house-frelinghuysen-supports-it/comment-page-1/|website=Morristown Green|accessdate=20 December 2017}}</ref> In 2016, Smith was one of four Republicans to receive a 100% rating from the Brady Campaign to Prevent Gun Violence and has generally received low or intermediate ratings from pro-gun organizations Gun Owners of America and the National Rifle Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/26952/chris-smith/37|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Vote Smart}}</ref>\n\nSmith did not co-sponsor the Brady Campaign's proposed legislation to expand background checks for gun purchasers and did not receive any contributions from the corporate gun lobby. Smith was one of only two Republicans in the New Jersey delegation not identified by the Brady Campaign as a \"lapdog\" for corporate gun lobbyists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lapdogscorecard.org|title=Is Your Member of Congress a Lapdog for the Corporate Gun Lobby?|website=Finish the Job Scorecard: Lap Dog Edition}}</ref>\n\n==== Mass shootings ====\n\nAfter the [[2016 Orlando nightclub shooting]], Smith offered his thoughts and prayers to the victims and their families and friends. He expresses concern with \"radical Islamist ideology.\"<ref name=\"Berkowitz61616\">{{cite web|last1=Berkowitz|first1=Bonnie|last2=Cai|first2=Weiyi|last3=Lu|first3=Denise|last4=Gamio|first4=Lazaro|title=Everything lawmakers said (and didn't say) after the Orlando mass shooting|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/national/how-lawmakers-responded-to-the-orlando-mass-shooting/|website=Washington Post|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the [[2017 Las Vegas shooting]], Smith co-sponsored a ban on [[bump stock]]s with [[Leonard Lance]].<ref name=\"Salant101317\">{{cite web|last1=Salant|first1=Jonathan D.|title=What Americans think about gun control after Las Vegas massacre|url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2017/10/what_americans_think_about_gun_control_after_las_vegas_massacre.html|website=NJ.com|accessdate=20 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Health care===\nSmith has written three major laws to address [[autism]], including the most recent Autism CARES which included $1.3 billion in funding for research, services and supports and requires a report on aging out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chrissmith.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=390105|title=Smith's $1.3 Billion Autism Bill on Way to President's Desk|date=2014-08-01|website=Chris Smith|access-date=2016-10-28}}</ref>\n\nOn May 9, 2014, Smith introduced the bill [[Autism CARES Act of 2014]], a bill that would amend the [[Public Health Service Act]] to reauthorize research, surveillance, and education activities related to [[autism spectrum disorders]] (autism) conducted by various agencies within the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services]] (HHS).<ref name=\"cbo4631\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45460|title=CBO \u2013 H.R. 4631|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=June 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Human rights===\nSmith advocates for [[human rights]], serving on numerous committees that seek to impact both national and international laws and legislation. He has stated that the bills he introduces to the house are meant to make the U.S. take \"human rights seriously.\"<ref name=\"Kim11511\">{{cite web|last1=Kim|first1=Susanna|title=Bill Targets Human Rights Offenders|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/woman-china-forced-abortions-leaves-unable-children/story?id=14880884|website=ABC News|accessdate=December 21, 2017|date=November 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Smith proposed, as part of the American Embassy Security Act, to stop a U.S. sponsored program which provided training to [[Royal Ulster Constabulary]] with the [[FBI]], due to claims of [[human rights]] violations, i.e. harassment of defense attorneys representing republicans in [[Northern Ireland]].<ref name=\"IrishTimes1999\">{{cite web|title=FBI training of RUC officers is suspended|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/fbi-training-of-ruc-officers-is-suspended-1.209448|website=The Irish Times|accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe supported the return David Goldman's son in the [[Goldman child abduction case]], which involved a trip to [[Brazil]].<ref name=\"Braun83109\"/> Smith acknowledges the [[Armenian Genocide]] and has made calls for the U.S. to recognize it.<ref name=\"SmithAPP41415\">{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Chris|title=SMITH: U.S. must end its denial of Armenian genocide|url=http://www.app.com/story/opinion/columnists/2015/04/14/armenian-genocide-rep-chris-smith/25778485|website=Asbury Park Press|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref> \n\nIn 2017, Smith co-sponsored an effort to prioritize [[human rights in Azerbaijan]] with [[Jim McGovern (American politician)|Jim McGovern]]. The H. Res. 537 act also seeks to see further implementation of the [[Magnitsky Act]] regarding Azerbaijani officials, as well as a call for Azerbaijan to release all political prisoners.<ref name=\"Armenian92717\">{{cite web|title=Representatives Chris Smith and Jim McGovern Urge Congress Hold Azerbaijan Accountable for Human Rights Abuses|url=https://armenianweekly.com/2017/09/27/smith-mcgovern-az|website=The Armenian Weekly|accessdate=December 21, 2017|date=September 27, 2017}}</ref> He supports efforts to deport [[Jakiw Palij]], a [[List of denaturalized former citizens of the United States|denaturalized former American citizen]] residing in New York who failed to disclose he worked as a guard at a [[concentration camp]] in [[Nazi Germany]].<ref name=\"Blau82317\">{{cite web|last1=Blau|first1=Reuven|title=Bipartisan group urges Tillerson to deport Nazi living in Queens|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/bipartisan-group-urges-tillerson-deport-nazi-living-queens-article-1.3436534|website=NY Daily News|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====China====\nSmith has held congressional hearings and has proposed bills regarding human rights violations, specifically around women's sexual health, activism and religious groups, in China. He staunchly opposes the forced [[sterilization (medicine)|sterilization]] and forced abortions being implemented by the Chinese government towards women regarding China's [[one-child policy]]. Regarding the victimization of these women, Smith stated that \"the agony that those women carry with them is beyond words. They talk about the pain that they carry for their child and for the violation by the state.\" In response, Smith wrote a bill, which was put into law in 1999, making it illegal for the U.S. to issue visas to [[foreign national]]s who have been involved in forced abortion or sterilization.<ref name=\"Kim11511\"/>\n\nSmith held a congressional hearing regarding the disappearance of blind Chinese activist [[Chen Guangcheng]].<ref name=\"Kim11511\"/> He attempted, in 2011, to visit Chen in China, when the activist was under [[house arrest]], but was not granted permission.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jsPMWMLFWn0qnAbT8AgNP8_Dlabw?docId=CNG.f7fee1d3e211a5423a39162aa46fc669.01|title=US lawmaker seeks to visit blind China rights lawyer|date=November 1, 2011|agency=Agence France-Presse|publisher=Google News|accessdate=April 27, 2012|archivedate=May 24, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120524091321/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jsPMWMLFWn0qnAbT8AgNP8_Dlabw?docId=CNG.f7fee1d3e211a5423a39162aa46fc669.01|deadurl=no}}</ref> In response to the violations towards Chen and his family, Smith sponsored the [[China Democracy Promotion Act of 2011]], which sought to prevent known Chinese human rights violators from entering the U.S.<ref name=\"Kim11511\"/>\n\nIn the wake of the [[2014 Hong Kong class boycott campaign]] and [[Umbrella Movement]], Smith co-sponsored the bipartisan [[Hong Kong Human Rights and Democracy Act]], supporting [[Hong Kong]]'s ongoing autonomy and the human rights of those Hong Kongers involved in nonviolent protests and/or those who have had their rights violated by the Chinese government.<ref name=\"Reuters22715\">{{cite web|title=U.S. bill links Hong Kong economic privileges to autonomy|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-hongkong/u-s-bill-links-hong-kong-economic-privileges-to-autonomy-idUSKBN0LV2MV20150227|website=Reuters|accessdate=December 21, 2017|date=2015}}</ref>\n\n====Human trafficking====\nSmith has sponsored and written many policies and proposals regarding [[human trafficking]]. In 2000, he co-sponsored the [[Victims of Trafficking and Violence Protection Act of 2000]], which authorizes protections for undocumented immigrants who are victims of severe forms of trafficking and violence.<ref name=\"CBS1062000\">{{cite web|title=Law To Curb Human Trafficking|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/law-to-curb-human-trafficking|website=CBS|accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe law is now part of the Violence Against Women Act. In 2017, Smith co-sponsored the [[Frederick Douglass Trafficking Victims Prevention and Protection Reauthorization Act]], alongside [[Karen Bass]]. The proposal funds programs that train employers to identify potential victims of human trafficking, prevents the sale of American goods made with forced labor, and provides educational tools and opportunities for children to learn how to avoid traffickers. The bill passed the House and has yet to go to the Senate.<ref name=\"Kinery71217\">{{cite web|last1=Kinery|first1=Emma|title=House passes sweeping overhaul of law to combat human trafficking|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2017/07/12/house-passes-sweeping-overhaul-law-combat-human-trafficking/473550001/|website=USA TODAY|accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"GovTrackFD\">{{cite web|title=Frederick Douglass Trafficking Victims Prevention and Protection Reauthorization Act of 2017 (H.R. 2200)|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/115/hr2200|website=GovTrack.us|accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Religion====\nSmith supports religious rights regarding international human rights. He supports sanctions against Vietnam regarding their treatment of the Catholics and China regarding the [[Uyghurs]] and [[Falun Gong]].<ref name=\"Braun83109\">{{cite web|last1=Braun|first1=Bob|title=N.J. Congressman Chris Smith fights for human rights without compromises|url=http://blog.nj.com/njv_bob_braun/2009/08/nj_congressman_chris_smith_fig.html|website=NJ.com|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\nSmith supported the [[Indonesian Family Refugee Protection Act]] in 2012, which would have extended the deadline for [[Indonesians|Indonesian]] immigrants to file for citizenship.<ref name=\"Giambusso32012\">{{cite web|last1=Giambusso|first1=David|title=Despite N.J. church's effort, Indonesian immigrant deported|url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2012/03/despite_nj_churchs_effort_indo.html|website=NJ.com|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Intellectual property rights===\nSmith authored the Global Online Freedom Act in 2007, but it did not become law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/democracy-post/wp/2017/08/14/what-the-united-states-can-do-to-protect-internet-freedom-around-the-world/|title=Opinion {{!}} What the United States can do to protect Internet freedom around the world|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2018-08-17}}</ref>  The proposed legislation was a bill  \"to promote freedom of expression on the Internet, to protect United States businesses from coercion to participate in repression by authoritarian foreign governments, and for other purposes.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/110th-congress/house-bill/275/text#toc-H261FFCAD0B1348A8BFA49800B1D5C07|title=Text - H.R.275 - 110th Congress (2007-2008): Global Online Freedom Act of 2007|last=Christopher|first=Smith,|date=2008-02-22|website=www.congress.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-08-17}}</ref>  Specifically, the bill would prohibit American companies from turning over data about customers residing in \"internet restrictive countries.\" The bill is supported by [[Amnesty International]], [[Human Rights Watch]] and [[Reporters Without Borders]]. It is opposed by the [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]].<ref name=\"Stirland42808\">{{cite web|last1=Sarah|first1=Lai Stirland|title=Ahead of Olympics, Congressman Pushes 'Global Online Freedom Act'|url=https://www.wired.com/2008/04/republican-hous|website=WIRED|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===LGBT rights===\nSmith has a \"0\" rating from the [[Human Rights Campaign]] regarding [[LGBTQ rights]];<ref name=\"HRC114\">{{cite book|title=Congressional Scorecard: Measuring Support for Equality in the 114th Congress|date=2016|page=18|url=http://assets2.hrc.org/files/assets/resources/114thCongressionalScorecard.pdf|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref> he does not support [[same-sex marriage]] and does not consider it a human right.<ref name=\"Salant2515\">{{cite web|last1=Salant|first1=Jonathan D.|title=N.J. Rep. Smith's gay marriage comments draw rebuke from fellow N.J. Rep. Pallone|url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/02/nj_rep_smiths_comments_on_gay_rights_draw_rebuke_f.html|website=NJ.com|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Smith said that children would be better off in orphanages than getting adopted by LGBT families.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2018/09/12/gop-lawmaker-caught-on-tape-saying-orphanage-better-than-gay-adoption/|title=EXCLUSIVE VIDEO: GOP lawmaker caught on tape: Orphanages better than gay adoption|date=2018-09-12|work=Washington Blade: Gay News, Politics, LGBT Rights|access-date=2018-09-21|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Labor movement ===\n\n{{BLP sources section|date=August 2018}}Smith is, by his own account, [[pro-labor]], and considers labor issues a \"human rights issue.\" He supports the [[Employee Free Choice Act]].<ref name=\"Braun83109\"/> The AFL-CIO Legislative Scorecard, which tracks support for workers' rights, gives Smith a 61% lifetime rating, ranking him seventh of New Jersey's twelve Representatives, and 195th of the [[United States House of Representatives|\nHouse's]] 435 Representatives.<ref name=\"AFL-CIO\">{{cite web |title=AFL-CIO Legislative Scorecard |url=https://aflcio.org/what-unions-do/social-economic-justice/advocacy/scorecard/us-house-scorecard |website=afl-cio.org |publisher=AFL-CIO |accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Marijuana ===\n\nSmith has a \"D\" rating from [[NORML]] regarding his voting record on [[cannabis]]-related matters. He has consistently voted against the Veterans Equal Access Amendment, which provides veterans access to information regarding medical marijuana accessibility in their respective states.<ref name=\"NORML\">{{cite web|title=New Jersey Scorecard |publisher=NORML |url=http://norml.org/congressional-scorecard/new-jersey|website=norml.org|accessdate=21 December 2017|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n===Military===\nBob Wallace, executive director of the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]] calls Smith \"the best friend\" of veterans. In 2004, Smith refused to endorse the Republican budget proposal unless it included more money for veterans. In a congressional hearing, Smith publicly articulated his belief that the Bush Administration's budget request was $1.2 billion less than the Department of Veterans Affairs actually required, embarrassing the administration and Republican congressional leadership.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Urbina|first1=Ian|title=Groups Protest Ouster of Veterans' Committee Chief|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/07/nyregion/groups-protest-ouster-of-veterans-committee-chief.html|website=The New York Times|accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref> In 2005, Smith was removed from his chairmanship and membership on the Veterans Affair Committee for his aggressive role in seeking more funding for veteran-related causes.<ref name=\"Braun83109\"/>\n\n===Science policy===\nSmith supports efforts to provide alternatives to [[embryonic stem cell research]]. In 2005, he co-sponsored a bill with [[Artur Davis]] to fund the creation of a network of national [[blood bank]]s to distribute [[umbilical cord]] blood for stem cell research.<ref name=\"Lang52405\">{{cite web|last1=Lang|first1=Thomas|title=Getting It Right on Stem Cell Legislation|url=http://archives.cjr.org/politics/getting_it_right_on_stem_cell.php|website=Columbia Journalism Review|accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Tax reform===\nSmith voted against the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]], joining four other Republican representatives from New Jersey. Regarding his vote, he stated that \"We need tax relief, but we must have relief that is not comparatively unfair to the taxpayers of New Jersey.\"<ref name=\"Salant122017\">{{cite web|last1=Salant|first1=Jonathan D.|title=Senate passes Trump-backed bill shrinking your big tax break|url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2017/12/bill_shrinking_your_big_tax_break_passes_senate_en.html|website=NJ.com|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref> Smith said he would be \"forced to oppose\" more tax cuts if legislation included a provision \"permanently extending the $10,000 cap on the state and local tax (SALT) deduction\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jagoda |first1=Naomi |title=Blue-state Republicans say they will vote against 'tax cuts 2.0' if it extends SALT cap |url=https://thehill.com/policy/finance/406238-blue-state-republicans-say-they-will-vote-against-tax-cuts-20-if-it-cements |website=The Hill |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{s-start}}\n|+ {{ushr|New Jersey|4|}}: Results 1980\u20132016<ref name=\"clerk\">{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/index.html|title=Office of the House Clerk \u2013 Electoral Statistics|publisher=Clerk of the United States House of Representatives|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070725184700/http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/index.html|archivedate=July 25, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"fedelect\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fec.gov/pubrec/electionresults.shtml|title=Election Results|publisher=[[Federal Election Commission]]|accessdate=October 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.gov/state/elections/2012-results/2012-official-general-results-house-of-representatives-020513.pdf|title=Official List \u2013 Candidates for House of Representatives For GENERAL ELECTION 11/06/2012 Election|date=2013-01-22|publisher=New Jersey Division of Elections|accessdate=July 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.gov/state/elections/2014-results/2014-official-general-results-us-house.pdf|title=Official List \u2013 Candidates for House of Representatives For GENERAL ELECTION 11/04/2014 Election|date=2014-12-02|publisher=New Jersey Department of State|accessdate=October 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nj.gov/state/elections/2016-results/2016-official-general-results-house-of-representatives.pdf|title=Official List \u2013 Candidates for House of Representatives For GENERAL ELECTION 11/08/2016 Election|date=2016-12-06|publisher=New Jersey Division of Elections|accessdate=May 20, 2017}}</ref>\n! Year\n!\n! Republican\n! Votes\n! %\n!\n! Democratic\n! Votes\n! %\n!\n! Third Party\n! Party\n! Votes\n! %\n!\n! Third Party\n! Party\n! Votes\n! %\n!\n|-\n|[[United States House election, 1980|1980]]\n||\n|{{party shading